The $config array stores the values read in from Solar.config.php,
also known as the [Main::ConfigFile config file].  In general, you
should not access the $config property directly; instead, read from
it using Solar::config().

When you call Solar::start(), this array will be populated with
the config file values (or the values from the alternative config
source you pass in).

You can configure the Solar class using these keys in your [Main::ConfigFile config file] (which are then passed into the Solar::$config property).

||~ key ||~ type ||~ value ||
|| `locale` || string || path to Solar locale directory, default `Solar/Locale` ||
|| `locale_code` || string || initial locale code, default `en_US` ||
|| `ini_set` || array || [[php ini_set()]] parameters ||
|| `start` || array || custom startup scripts ||
|| `stop` || array || custom shutdown scripts ||

++ `ini_set`

These config key values get called as part of the Solar::start() process.  For example, if you have this in Solar::$config ...

<code type="php">
$config['Solar']['ini_set']['display_errors'] = true;
</code>

... Solar::start() will issue `ini_set('display_errors', true)` as part of the startup process.

++ `start`

These values represent scripts to execute as part of Solar::start().  For example, if you have this in Solar::$config ...

<code type="php">
$config['Solar']['start'][] = '/path/to/start1.php';
$config['Solar']['start'][] = '/path/to/start2.php';
</code>

... then Solar::start() will run `start1.php` and `start2.php` as part of its startup process.

++ `stop`

These values represent scripts to execute as part of Solar::stop().  For example, if you have this in Solar::$config ...

<code type="php">
$config['Solar']['stop'][] = '/path/to/stop1.php';
$config['Solar']['stop'][] = '/path/to/stop2.php';
</code>

... then Solar::stop() will run `stop1.php` and `stop2.php` as part of its shutdown process.